Predictive-Modelling-Using-Social-Profile-in-Online-P2P-Lending-Financial-Market-¶

Both of financial data and social data are crucial for loans prediction. So, in this project we analyzed the dynamics of loans based on both financial and social data.

Understanding the Dataset¶

  • the data consists of two main tyoes of features social and financial features.

  • our data consisting of many kinds of data: discrete features, continous features, categorical features, date features, boolen features and key features.

  • so we need to deal with these data.

  • The label of the dataset is loan status the loan should be paid or not.

Preprocessing¶

  • first of all, we the dealed with the missing data as follows:

  • we explored the variable definetion file to understand the variables more and more and to see if there are some values that are missing but in fact they are just doesn't exist and we created new features to deal with them discussed in the Feature Engineering part

  • we the dealed with the missing data that is actually missing as follows: after we separate the features contain missing data we lassified them as numeric and categoric. we could find that the numeric features that contain missing values are skewed so we prefered to use the median to replace the missing values. and then we moved on to categorical features that contain missing values we replaced them by the mode.

  • Secondlly

Feature Engineering¶

  • Here we created almost 15 new feature to explain the missing data that is actually doesn't exist some of these features discussed below:

  • after_July2009: used to explain the missing data in EstimatedEffectiveYield, EstimatedLoss, EstimatedReturn, ProsperRating (numeric), ProsperRating (Alpha) and ProsperScore as these features are Applicable for loans originated after July 2009

  • had_PriorLoans: used to explain the missing data in TotalProsperLoans, TotalProsperPaymentsBilled, OnTimeProsperPayments, ProsperPaymentsLessThanOneMonthLate, ProsperPaymentsOneMonthPlusLate, ProsperPrincipalBorrowed, ProsperPrincipalOutstanding and ScorexChangeAtTimeOfListing as these features doesn't exist if the borrower had no prior loans

  • NoTE: you can find more in our notebook

Model Building¶

Metrics considered for Model Evaluation¶

ROC, AUC score, Accuracy , Precision , Recall and F1 Score

  • ROC: it's a graph that provides a simple way to summaries all of the information its a plot betwwen False positve rate and true positive rate.
  • AUC: it's the area under the roc curve.
  • Accuracy: What proportion of actual positives and negatives is correctly classified?
  • Precision: What proportion of predicted positives are truly positive ?
  • Recall: What proportion of actual positives is correctly classified ?
  • F1 Score : Harmonic mean of Precision and Recall.

Logistic Regression¶

  • Logistic Regression helps find how probabilities are changed with actions.
  • The function is defined as P(y) = 1 / 1+e^-(A+Bx)
  • Logistic regression involves finding the best fit S-curve where A is the intercept and B is the regression coefficient. The output of logistic regression is a probability score.
  • Used to predict if the loan should be paid or not

Neural Networks¶

  • NN is a Machine Learning model inspired by the networks of biological neurons found in our brains.
  • NNs are at the very core of Deep Learning. They are versatile, powerful, and scalable, making them ideal to tackle large and highly complex Machine Learning tasks, such as classifying billions of images.
  • Used to see how the risk is if, we accepepted the loan

Naive Bayes¶

  • Naive Bayes methods are a set of supervised learning algorithms based on applying Bayes theorem with the naive assumption of conditional independence between every pair of features given the value of the class variable. https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/naive_bayes.html?highlight=naive+bayes
  • Again used to predict if the loan should be paid or not

Decision Tree Classifier¶

  • Decision Trees (DTs) are a non-parametric supervised learning method used for classification and regression. The goal is to create a model that predicts the value of a target variable by learning simple decision rules inferred from the data features. A tree can be seen as a piecewise constant approximation.
  • Again used to see how the risk is, if we accepepted the loan

Choosing the features¶

  • After training our models we used elif and features importance for feature selection we applied this for logistic regression, naive bayes and decision tree classifier and the result was as followes:

  • When we apply the logistic regression model the accuracy dropped from 100% to 99%.

  • When we apply naive bayes model the accuracy dropped from 92% to 90%.
  • When we apply decision tree classifier model the accuracy dropped from 59% to 59%.

ROI¶

  • Return on investment (ROI) is a performance measure used to evaluate the efficiency or profitability of an investment or compare the efficiency of a number of different investments. ROI tries to directly measure the amount of return on a particular investment, relative to the investments cost.
  • we used the following formula: ROI = (Gain - Cost of Investment) / Cost of Investment

Features used¶

All the features that is used for the final model:¶
  • LP_CustomerPrincipalPayments: Pre charge-off cumulative principal payments made by the borrower on the loan. If the loan has charged off, this value will exclude any recoveries.
  • LoanCurrentDaysDelinquent: The number of days delinquent.
  • LoanMonthsSinceOrigination: Number of months since the loan originated.
  • LP_ServiceFees: Cumulative service fees paid by the investors who have invested in the loan.
  • MonthlyLoanPayment: The scheduled monthly loan payment.
  • LoanOriginalAmount: The origination amount of the loan.
  • BorrowerAPR: The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.
  • EstimatedEffectiveYield:
  • after_July2009: for loans originated after July 2009 the value will be 1, otherwise 0
  • CreditGrade_Not_Applicable: Applicable for listings pre-2009 period and will only be populated for those listings. If applicable the value will be 1 otherwise 0
  • Term: The length of the loan expressed in months.
  • Investors: The number of investors that funded the loan.
  • Occupation_Professional: The Occupation selected by the Borrower at the time they created the listing.If Professional the value will be 1 otherwise 0
  • Occupation_Retail Management: The Occupation selected by the Borrower at the time they created the listing.If Retail Management the value will be 1 otherwise 0
  • BorrowerState_NC: The two letter abbreviation of the state of the address of the borrower at the time the Listing was created. If NC the value will be 1 otherwise 0
  • AvailableBankcardCredit: The total available credit via bank card at the time the credit profile was pulled.
  • Occupation_Sales - Retail: The Occupation selected by the Borrower at the time they created the listing.If Sales - Retail the value will be 1 otherwise 0
  • StatedMonthlyIncome: The monthly income the borrower stated at the time the listing was created.
  • BorrowerState_OK: The two letter abbreviation of the state of the address of the borrower at the time the Listing was created. If OK the value will be 1 otherwise 0
  • Recommendations: Number of recommendations the borrower had at the time the listing was created.
  • Interest Rate: The Borrower's interest rate for this loan.
